<sn><md>#### We Observe:

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
- **Rate of Profit:** A profit of Tk. 100 in 1 year is called the rate of profit or percentage of profit per annum.

- **Period of Time:** The time for which a profit is calculated is called the period of time.

- **Simple Profit:** The profit which is accounted each year **only on the primary or initial principal** is called the simple profit. Usually, profit means the simple profit.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-6

Algebraic Symbols Used in This Chapter:

| Symbol | Meaning |
|--------|---------|
| $P$ | Principal |
| $r$ | Rate of profit (rate of interest) |
| $n$ | Time |
| $I$ | Profit |
| $A$ | Profit-principal (total amount) = Principal + Profit |

:::
:::

**Relations:**
- $A = P + I$
- $P = A - I$
- $I = A - P$

Which gives:

- Profit-principal = Principal + Profit,  <br>  $A = P + I$
- $P = A - I$
- $I = A - P$

If any three of the four data namely principal, rate of profit, time and profit are known, the remaining one can be found.
</md></sn><sn><md>#### Formula

&gt; Profit = $\text{Principal} \cdot \text{Rate of Profit} \cdot \text{time}$ <br>
&gt; $I = P \cdot r \cdot n$ <br>
&gt; $A = P + I = P + Prn = P(1 + rn)$

where,
- $I$ = Profit
- $P$ = Principal
- $r$ = Rate of profit
- $n$ = Time
- $A$ = Profit-principal (total amount)

</md></sn><sn></sn>